segments.text: So while the mic was off on a half-time teaching.
And on a half-time teaching appointment.
Now officially then you were to be half-time research, half-time teaching.
Right.
For the nine months?
For the 12 months.
For the 12 months.
I had a 12-month appointment.
I did not teach during the summer.
And what research facilities were you provided in those early years?
We had a laboratory, a small laboratory, one desk and things of the sort.
Provided some animal.
And your, was your funding for the research?
My funding for the research was, I had a good funding because researchers in this project, what they call S-10 Animal Breeding Project,
It was a regional breeding project and I had most of my animals that I was dealing with were either at McGregor or on the high plains of Texas.
I had some animals here and then I started going into sheep.
nutrition and because I could get a grant in antibiotics, I was the first, I think, in the country to feed oriomycin or chlorotetracycline to sheep.
That's an interesting anecdote that I'd like to tell about that first.
Please, please do.
One of the disease problems of sheep is that you... Well, at the time that I began most of my large animal work, there was what is known as the eye of the master fattens the animal.
In other words, you have to have a person that goes in and observes animals, and particularly each animal, and then pulls feed away from them and do this kind of thing.
And so we decided to self-feed.
a fellow professor in animal science, a young man by the name of Bill Comlottie.
He was the son of the famed Bill Comlottie in Illinois.
He knew more about sheep than I ever knew in the rest of my life, but we got together and he said, let's self-feed him.
And I said, okay.
Now, nobody had ever self-fed a sheep before.
So we brought the sheep in and divided them up
and dumped the feed into some feeders.
And sure enough, what happened was they died.
They died of enterotoxemia, overeating disease.
Well, Dr. Miller, Jack Miller, was head of the department at that particular point.
And he called me in because he was supporting my research.
He'd buy the animals and he'd hoped when I got through with them I could get the money back by selling them.
We didn't mind anything.
We fed them whatever we fed them and then took them to market.
And we weren't worried about that particular point of things that might go and get into the food chain or things of that sort.
At any rate, the animals died, and so he stood me up in the corner, and Bill Comlottie was in there, and he said, Harry, you don't know how to feed sheep.
He says, I don't want you to do anything about feeding sheep again.
I don't want you to ever feed sheep unless you go with Bill Comlottie.
Well, Bill Comlottie had been absolutely quiet in the situation.
So after Dr. Miller got through, I said, well, Dr. Miller, there's one thing you need to know.
The only sheep that died were in the controls.
we had now come up with a way which that went faster than anything else and even today they still use the same material.
So a controlled self-feeding is that what you're saying?
It was a controlled well the self-feeding everything was self-fed but the only animals that died
Oh, and from anaerotoxemia were those that received no antibiotic.
Oh, okay.
And the antibiotic completely prevented disease.
In those early years, how did a faculty member get evaluated and get any feedback from the department head or the dean about his performance?
How did you know whether you were being viewed as mostly, I think, because of salary and promotion?
But nobody called you in and as far as you knew, there was no written report.
As far as I know, there was no written report as far as that's concerned.
You see, I thought it was a little slow.
I was promoted to assistant professor after four years here.
You were an instructor.
I was an associate professor.
I mean, associate, okay.
So you came as an assistant.
I came as an assistant.
Then four years.
I was an associate after four years.
And then two years later, I was a full professor.
Six years out of, oh, that's fast.
Yeah.
And so I've spent, since that time, 1958 on, I have spent my life as a full professor.
You may be the senior full professor around here.
in terms of number of years as a full professor.
As a full professor, yeah.

During those years, was it like after I got here that normally the salary increases that mattered came the first year after the legislature met and then the second year of the biennium there wasn't much money for salary increases?
That's about right.
And your research and teaching continued.
When did you begin to get in and headed toward the administration?
Well, it started with the Century Study.
Oh, okay.
The Aspirations Report.
The Aspirations Report.
Oh, that's great.
How did you get appointed?
Do you have any idea?
I have no idea.
I just woke up one day and they said you were it.
And I was chairman of the research committee.
And yours truly was the secretary
of the other part and he doesn't know how he got appointed either.
It just and so we wrote the report and apparently it was strong enough that in
Well, there was one other thing that happened.
You see, up until 1960, I was single.
Mm-hm.
And I married in 1960.
Okay.
And the summer of 1962, I was invited to be a visiting professor at Cornell University to teach a course in biochemistry.
Mm-hm.
Well, I borrowed the notes from Mac Prescott and went on up and had a good time during the summer.
Mm-hm.
And they were looking at me pretty heavily.
And I don't know, it wasn't anything formal or anything of a sort.
But the day before I left, the head of department calls me up and says, we'd like to hire you.
So I came back with a job offer.
Again, there was no interview or anything in particular, any review or anything of a sort.
Well, at that point, R.E.
Patterson says, I want you to be, and Earl Rudder says, I want you to be associate director of the Experiment Station.
This is 1962.
And so by December 1, it was...

associate director of the experiment station and so hey I was teaching you see at that particular point so Bill Ellis came down and taught my 303 of course and I was teaching the biochemical genetics course and I kept on with that until I finished but there was no one that could pick that one up until you know the semesters went on into January
at that particular point in time.
All right, now let's back up on the campus administration.
When you came, who was the Dean of Agriculture?
Charles Shepardson.
Shepardson?
Shepardson.
Spell, I don't know that name.
S-H-E-P... H-S-H-E-P-A-R-D-S-O-N, I think it is, Shepardson.
And then when, who follows him?
Jack Miller.
And then Patterson?
No.
Gus Watkins as dean.
Oh, okay.
And Gus Watkins was demoted to, well, his title was demoted to director of agricultural instruction, and Patterson assumed the title of dean.
And then when Artie Lewis, Don Lewis retired, he assumed the title of Director of the Experiment Station and I went in as Associate Dean, Associate Director.
Alright, when in those, in the early 50s, the administrative structure at that point
The dean of agriculture, did the Experiment Station and Extension Service report to the dean in the early 50s?
No.
They were separate.
They were separate.
And for you and your colleagues in the 50s, did you all have a perception of the president and how he was getting along?
Who was president when you got here in the 50s?
I don't recall.
Gilchrist or Bolton?
No, I think Gilchrist was chancellor at that particular point.
Bolton probably.
Mary Trax, Bolton.
Yeah.
Did you all see much of the entire administration?
I saw.
I paid little or no attention to the presidency.
And did you see much of the board of directors it was then called?
I saw absolutely nothing of it.
And then Morgan,
was here in the... David Morgan, yes.
And he had some plans for changing A&M, but he didn't survive.
Was there much sentiment among the faculty at that point?
I didn't sense anything.
Because you see, generally, I was doing my duty and I was trying to do this.
And then when we had the opportunity for the central study, the centennial study, that was a point in which we could get our ideas put together.
And of course, at that point, Earl Rudder was president.
Do you remember any reaction when he was appointed president among faculty types?
Well, I wondered what a guy who didn't have a PhD was going to do.
You weren't acquainted with him at that time, were you?
No, I was acquainted with him.
How?
I was in the Army Reserves.
Oh, sure, sure.
And I was in his division.
Describe him as a reserve general.
He was a magnificent reserve general, and so I began to know him, and we became acquainted there.
And in a sense, I was one of the cronies that he appointed.
And let's see, did you all go to Austin for meetings?
No, we had our local meetings here, but for summer camp, we'd go to Fort Hood, North Fort Hood.
And now your your appointment by him in the reserve was after he got here or did you know him?
No no I knew him before he got here so I was well acquainted with him before he arrived and as a matter of fact they people would call me up and said what do you know about this guy Earl Rudder?
And what would you have told them?
I told them he's all right he'll work out
describe him in personality and style and manner before he became president?
I don't think it was much different from what that was because he was a politician then.
And his remarkable situation was that he was doing things that he thought he could sell as a political man.
Now, he didn't have to do that because he was a military man.
And in the military, he was the boss.
He was a commanding officer.

He was a colonel when I first knew him and he got a star soon thereafter and I'm not sure when he got the second star but in the process it would but we'd run into him and he was then he was running for land commissioner
I have a chance to run into him up there and we'd chat.
I learned to know Margaret, and so I knew him before he came.
All right, and when he came here, do you remember any early speeches or anything public that he did as the new president?
Not really, no.
No, I don't remember.
Because I got here in the fall of 59 and I don't remember seeing much of him.
No.
And I remember him some, am I correct in remembering that he sometimes would mention that he didn't, wasn't very good at making speeches and he knew it?
I suspect I've heard him say that, but I never paid much attention.
That didn't bother me.
Did he, did you all see him ever come around in the animal sciences building?
No.
Or should I say Animal Industries Building?
Animal Industries.
No, as a matter of fact, I didn't.
But of course, O.D.
Butler was a colonel, you know, a lieutenant colonel at that particular point.
He was commanding officer and I was in O.D.
's battalion.
Was O.D.
the department head of animal science by then?
He became department head, I think, in 1956.
Oh, okay.
So he's department head.
Yeah, that's when Jack Miller went over to be dean.
All right, this committee, this century study and the aspirations report and so forth, describe as much as you can remember about that.
Who, how, what, where, and so forth.
Well,
I remember meeting, and several times, Bill Barzac, the late Bill Barzac, was appointed, I called the Dean of Liberal Arts and asked for a person to work with me.
And he appointed Bill Bartak, so Bill Bartak was the secretary and the guy who put it all together.
And the person that seemed to stand out more than anybody else or two was Bruno Swalinski.
Mm-hm.
And
The general consensus of that situation was that what we had to do was to move basically into science.
And then at that point in time, I wrote a section on that on the research and extension centers that I call them research stations now or substations.
That they needed to have extension people with them as well as they need to be education units as well as anything else.
And that report was accepted, and I think pretty well accepted in total.
It didn't have the conflicts that the teaching did.
Because I was the secretary of that other half, I remember that.
And your committee met about how often?
Once a week?
Once every week or once every couple of weeks or something of that sort.
Eight, fifteen, eighteen members?
About that.
Was there any dissension that you remember at all in the... No, but there was some vigorous discussion.
With Bruno there, obviously.
And one of them said, we've got to do this kind of a thing.
And I would sort of look up and wonder about it.
Was there ever any attempt by any outside administrator, board member, a former student, or anybody else to interject something into the committee's actions?
Not that I know of.
I never heard of it either.
Not that I know of.
And no reporters?
No reporters.
And the report was given, summarized, and... And how did you all feel when officially, finally, all of this was, of the report was accepted?
I thought we felt, we were, we expected it to be.
What did you and your colleagues, what was the reaction when you heard about the recommendations of co-education, non-compulsory core, racial integration, broadened curriculum?
I think fundamentally we were all in agreement with it.
At least I was.
I don't remember any campus.
About that time the A&M Mothers Club had named me professor of
at the time, and they had a luncheon for me here.
And after the luncheon, Beverly made a few of them very angry because she was definitely for co-education.
And of course, these mothers said, no, they wouldn't do that.
So finally, Beverly said to these ladies, she said, suppose your daughter married one of these people.
Would you deny her an education?
The conversation stopped.
I reported it to Errol Rudder and he says, good.
But I think there were some other problems or some other situations that you know more about than I do.
Did anyone ever in any manner contact you about the outside opposition to some of these changes?
Never.
No.
How did you and your colleagues feel when the board officially adopted those changes?
I think we were happy with it.
Now the official recommendation was to change the name, as it had been in many other states, to Texas State University.
I know.
What did you all think about that?
I think Texas A&M, good, why don't they get rid of that name?
Come on, come on, let's go with it, what everybody else does.
That was my, I think, the reaction generally.
Do you know who made the actual recommendation of what we now have as the name?
I think it was Earl Rutter, wasn't it?
Wayne Hall.
Wayne Hall.
Mr. Rutter was very, very opposed to dropping the A&M.
Hall's the one that came up with the variety that we now, that the A&M is not an abbreviation, but in effect a logo with an ampersand, not the A&D.
And that the A and M are not abbreviations for agriculture and mechanical.
Well, in the year 2001, I'm damn glad it happened.
Yes.
It is a unique situation.
Well, after that, I said, well, you know, Texas A&M, Cornell,
They were the two I could think of as far as names are concerned, a straight university.
All right, now, and you were, began your administrative career now in 58?
No, I began it at 62.
And what were your duties when you first?
I was associate director of the agricultural experiments.
And what did the associate director really do?
Well, you began to approve projects, and you began to line up, and you suddenly realized that they were in charge of the budget.
And one of the biggest things you did was prepare the budgets and I ended up doing the budgets for both teaching and research for the Experiment Station.
I was really an assistant dean, associate dean as well.
Although I didn't have the title.
You reported to whom?
Patterson.
To Patterson.
And he was director of the Experiment Station.
He was director of the Experiment Station.
And your offices were?
In the Jack Williams Building.
What we used to call the System Building.
The System Building.
And the Dean of Agriculture at that time
Was that Gus?
That was Gus and he was maneuvered into a position that took him to the Dominican Republic.
And so Richard Potts, Dick Potts, came over as an assistant dean at that point and handled the students.
So the dean's office actually moved over
And Patterson then became director and dean?
Director, dean and director.
Dean and director.

Now Extension Service remained separate and they were across the hall and they were in almost an autonomous kind of a thing and Patterson had his problems with that more than anything else because he was trying to downgrade the power of the county agent.
And that didn't work, and the county ignored the boom on him.
And so I don't know.
He and Earl Rudder became cross with each other, and so he resigned in 1967.
As the associate director of the Experiment Station, what were the problems that you had to cope with?
Well, my problem was, and I guess I was a little nasty, because we took a trip by airplane.
with the Board of Regents.
And I was asked essentially to make a description of where we were going, and Patterson was sitting there doing it.
So here we was, you know, I was separating it out.
And Patterson, I guess he was, but he never, well, he wanted me to,
incorporate the extension service under this and as you know that was never accomplished until year before last or last year.
Now during those same years in the early 60s Mr. Rutter in fact became the chief executive officer of not only the campus but also the system.
He was president of both.
Yes.
When that occurred, did that make the administrative task of you and your colleagues easier or more difficult?
It made it different in the sense that the academic vice president, I reported to the academic vice president relative to the teaching end of things and the budget situation there.
and all other matters I reported directly to Earl Rudder.
Right, and although you were associate director at that time, were you in fact the chief academic officer for the Experiment Station?
I think so.
And you reported to Wayne Hall?
For that Experiment Station, the dean.
Oh, you reported to the dean.
No, I did not become the chief executive officer of the college then, until the School of Agriculture, until September 1967, when I became acting dean and acting director.
All right, now what led to that change?
Well, Patterson's resignation.
Oh, okay, all right.
And as far as you know, what was the process that led to your being selected at that point?
It was an interesting process because I was told by Earl Rudder I did not have a chance to become dean.
He said, we're not going to make you dean.
We're not going to make you dean and director.
And said, then he followed up and says, who should we look at?
Well, I gave Earl Rudder a number of names, several names, and I think every one of them they brought in for interview.
As far as you know, who did the interviewing?
Was it Clyde Wells?
No, he wasn't chairman of the board at that point.
I bet it was.
It might have been.
At any rate, it was board members.
Board members.
And Rudder?
Rudder.
And they, since that time, at least two of them have become chancellors or presidents of universities and things of that sort.
So they weren't idled.
And the last one that they interviewed simply told Rudder, said, hell, you got Harry Kunkel here, why don't you pick him?
He's the most scholarly of them all.
That was the process.
Again, I never interviewed anybody for it.
Earl Rudder just called me up one day and said, I'd like to make you the dean.
And I said, well, give me a little time to think about it.
So I went down, and Beverly walked in about that point, and I told her that.
Describe, and so when you went over to chat with him, can you...
Went up.
His office.
That's right.
Can you describe the conversation when you chatted with him seriously about the task?
No, he says, I want to make a dean as far as this is concerned.
Did he give you any directions, guidance, advice?
Yeah, I think so.
He says, you're a young man.
You ought to do so-and-so.
He'd occasionally pop out.
He says, you're a young man.
You ought to do so-and-so.
He'd pop up with certain directions, specifics of his advice.
I don't remember, but generally they were good.
Did he give you any don'ts?
Don't do this, don't do that?
No.
Well, he'd just do something good.
Now, this is 1967.
This is 1967.
Well, by that time it was 1968.
And so March the 1st, 1968.
As far as you were aware at that point, was Mr. Rutter in good health?
I thought he was.
And who was the vice president for academic affairs then?
Because Hall had gone, hadn't he?
Who?
Wayne Hall had gone to Washington, D.C. Bill Graff?
Bill Graff, yeah.
Was Bill Graff ever vice president?
He was dean of... No, no, that's right.
He was, yeah.
Who?
Dean of faculty.
The geoscientists?
that came from Chicago was he the he was he was academic vice president and describe the scope of your responsibilities as dean I mean as director I was
chief executive officer of the college, or that was the college at that particular point in time.
I was chief executive officer as acting director, and I remained acting director for five years.
I was never officially appointed director.
I never asked for it.
But you still had the responsibility.
I still had the responsibility.
For five years I was an acting director.
And so the experiment station essentially was under eye.
And Hutchison, who was then, when I was named dean, was named associate dean, and he essentially was told to rip a port to me, which essentially worked out because he did.
And did you inherit any particular problems that needed
quick solution?
No.
I created the problem shortly thereafter.
I asked Jarvis Miller to become assistant director.
And why did you select Jarvis?
Well, he was a freshman.
He was a faculty member and he didn't have anything else to do.
Okay.
And so he was associate director reporting to you.
He was assistant director.
Assistant director.
And then as he worked along, he seemed to, he and I seemed to get along very well, so I appointed him as associate.
